  "prompt": "The bond angle of Sulphur dioxide is greater than that of Ozone. Why?",
  "response": "The bond angle of sulfur dioxide (SO\u2082) is greater than that of ozone (O\u2083) due to differences in their molecular structures and the distribution of lone pairs of electrons.\n\nIn sulfur dioxide, the sulfur atom is bonded to two oxygen atoms and has one lone pair of electrons. The molecular shape is bent or V-shaped, and the bond angle is approximately 119.5 degrees. According to the VSEPR (Valence Shell Electron Pair Repulsion) theory, the lone pair-bonding pair repulsion in SO\u2082 is less than the bonding pair-bonding pair repulsion because lone pairs occupy more space. This causes the bond angle to expand slightly from the ideal 120 degrees for a trigonal planar arrangement to about 119.5 degrees.\n\nIn contrast, ozone has a central oxygen atom bonded to two other oxygen atoms, forming a bent structure with a bond angle of approximately 116.8 degrees. Ozone has a resonance structure, which means it can be represented by multiple Lewis structures. It also has one lone pair on the central atom, which causes repulsion that reduces the bond angle compared to an ideal trigonal planar system.\n\nThe greater number of lone pairs in ozone compared to sulfur dioxide (after considering the bonding environment and resonance) leads to greater repulsion in the bent structure of ozone, thus resulting in a smaller bond angle compared to sulfur dioxide.",
